## 🧑‍🎓 voter/login.php — Key Section

```php
if($user && password_verify($_POST['password'], $user['password'])){
    $_SESSION['user'] = $user['id'];
```
**Why?** Unlike the admin login, voter login stores the **user ID** (integer) in the session, not the username. This is because the voter's ID is needed for database queries (like checking which elections they've voted in).

> **Note:** This login does NOT have the legacy plain-text password fallback. If your existing voters have plain-text passwords in the database, they won't be able to log in. You may want to add the legacy fallback here too, or update all existing passwords in the database.

---

## 🗳️ voter/vote.php — Key Security Checks

```php
// Check already voted
$stmt = $conn->prepare("SELECT id FROM votes WHERE user_id = ? AND election_id = ?");
```
**Why?** Before showing the voting form, check if this user already voted in this election. This is the **server-side enforcement** — even if someone manipulates the front-end, this database check prevents double voting.

```php
// Get election info
$stmt = $conn->prepare("SELECT title, end_date FROM elections WHERE id = ? AND status = 'Active'");
```
**Why?** The `AND status = 'Active'` condition ensures voters can only vote in **active** elections. If an admin has deactivated an election, this query returns nothing and the user gets redirected back.

```php
$stmt = $conn->prepare("UPDATE users SET has_voted = 1 WHERE id = ?");
```
**Why?** After casting a vote, mark the user as "has voted" in the users table. This is used on the admin voters list to show voted/not-voted status.

---

## 👤 voter/profile.php — Password Change Logic

```php
$valid = false;
if(password_verify($current_password, $user_data['password'])){
    $valid = true;
} elseif($user_data['password'] === $current_password) {
    $valid = true; // Legacy fallback
}
```
**Why?** Supports both old plain-text passwords AND new hashed passwords. When a voter changes their password through this form, their old plain-text password gets replaced with a properly hashed one — effectively **upgrading their security** without requiring a database migration.

